2) The first was a practical reason to compress, the second is more creative. Compression allows us to shape the envelope of sounds, by varying the attack and release and type of compressor we use (we'll come back to that). Why would that be useful? A few examples;

- A fast attack allows us to tame the front of a sound, and set it back in an arrangement. Our ears are naturally drawn to shorter sharper transients, and that can be a lovely thing. But say for example I've got a bright and transient heavy acoustic guitar, it might be distracting me from the vocal and the story of the song, a fast attack and low ratio could allow me to "set it back" behind the vocal, without turning it down or darkening it too much

- Another way we can use the envelope shaping is to bring out the body or thump in a sound. Take something like a bright snare crack, a compressor like a DBX160 will grab the front transient and soften it, and then the release curve will give the body and shell of the snare this chunky weight that can be really musical

@Edward Rivera Might need to buy tupe.

@JustinLeu maybe saturn is the solution here!

@Nick Stetina I have never used Kelvin! will look into it.

The Little Radiator is doing something cool for me right now and also messing with just the tape sat on EchoBoy. But Not totally sold. It's gonna be a huge part of the drum sound on these mixes

@Joe Thomas I know I threw a lot out there, hopefully something will trigger a creative solution!

When something doesn’t seem to ever be loud enough I try to mix it with the drums by themselves (so drums and bass) then slowly bring everything else in and make sure the bass doesn’t get lost with each addition.

Last thing - mixing bass NOT soloed can really help. You might push the knobs a lot farther that way if you’re actually trying to get it to push through a dense mix as opposed to by itself.

Really helpful, thanks all @Calvin Lauber @sethearnest @Will Melones .

@willmix.studio#0 My experience with this kind of work is minimal! The thinking behind separate channels per song would be say if the drum mix wanted to be significantly different on each track, and then also just having complete freedom to go nuts on a sound without having to do everything as automation (or forget to, then wonder why the balance on track 1 is suddenly fucked).

But like you’re saying @Calvin Lauber , I think that level of detail might be impractical given the sheer amount of work to get through, and also unnecessary since as you say, it’s pretty much just one drum sound for the whole set. Maybe I could dup a channel here and there if I really wanted to go nuts on one song.

@NoahNeedleman @cian riordan @Will Melones This is awesome, thank you for your thoughts!

@NoahNeedleman Wouldn't have considered drum tuning changes. I'd be thinking about that over takes of a studio track, and flipping playlists makes it easy to check on the same section, but in this context it's the sort of thing that would've tripped me up. Like, why is the snare thwacking in song 1, but it's thwocking in song 20? Would be easy to second guies, start EQing again and ruin the rest of the show. Absolutely if you're chatting to Kaplan, it'd be great to hear - I'm sure the Discord generally would appreciate but I'd love to get his inside track, please!

@cian riordan Great shout on mindset, thank you. As @Will Melones mentioned, the energy is already great so it's not like I'm going to have to do a lot of heavy lifting. In the words of @BatMeckley (referring to the OP-1 vs Ableton), sounds like this is one to ride like a surfboard rather than drive like a bus.
